  measureOf := by
    intro s
    if h : Real.pi ∈ s then 1 else 0
  empty := by
    simp [Set.mem_singleton_iff]
  mono {S T} hST := by
    by_cases h : Real.pi ∈ S
    · -- Case: Real.pi ∈ S
      have h₁ : Real.pi ∈ T := hST h
      simp_all [h, h₁]
      <;> norm_num
    · -- Case: Real.pi ∉ S
      have h₁ : Real.pi ∉ S := h
      by_cases h₂ : Real.pi ∈ T
      · -- Subcase: Real.pi ∈ T
        simp_all [h, h₂]
        <;> norm_num
      · -- Subcase: Real.pi ∉ T
        simp_all [h, h₂]
        <;> norm_num
``` 
No further steps are needed, as the problem statement specifically asked to replace only the last `sorry` (in the `mono` property of `μD`). 

### Final Notes

This proof works because the outer measure of the Dirac measure is defined to be `1` on sets containing `π` and `0` otherwise. The monotonicity follows trivially from the definition since `S ⊆ T` implies that if `π ∈ S` then `π ∈ T`, and no other case forces the measure of `T` to be smaller than that of `S`.

